   <titles>
      <title>The Projection of a Vector on a Line</title>
      <plain.title>Projection: Vector to Line</plain.title>
   </titles>
   <intro>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>Here we introduce a construction which appears in many contexts: how to project a vector <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                  </math> onto the line through the origin in the direction of another vector <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
                  </math>
               </para.body>
            </para>
            <media type="image" active="1" inline="0">
               <img src="ims/ProjectionVectorLine.png"/>
            </media>
            <para>
               <para.body>The picture above shows how the vector <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                  </math> gets projected orthogonally onto the line <math>
                     <latex>L</latex>
                  </math>. The result is the vector <math>
                     <latex>\pr_L(\Vect{x})</latex>
                  </math> which is
   		<subordinate>
                     <hot>colinear</hot>
                     <info>
                        <info.caption>What does ‘colinear’ mean?</info.caption>
                        <para>
                           <para.body>‘Colinear’ means ‘has the same direction as’.</para.body>
                        </para>
                     </info>
                  </subordinate> with <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
                  </math>. The following proposition tells us how to compute this projection vector.
			</para.body>
               <index.glossary>
                  <term>colinear</term>
                  <info>
                     <info.caption>What does ‘colinear’ mean?</info.caption>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>‘Colinear’ means ‘has the same direction as’.</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </info>
               </index.glossary>
            </para>
         </block.body>
      </block>
   </intro>
   <body>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <xi:include xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"
                        href="ProjectionVectorLine_Prop.xml"/>
            <def type="Notation" id="Notation_OrthogonalProjectionXAlongY">
               <def.body>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>We sometimes write <math>
                           <latex>\pr_{\Vect{y}}(\Vect{x})</latex>
                        </math> for <math>
                           <latex>\pr_{L}(\Vect{x})</latex>
                        </math>, and call it the orthogonal projection of <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                        </math> along <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
                        </math>.
			 The vector <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{u} = \Vect{x} - \pr_{\Vect{y}} (\Vect{x})</latex>
                        </math> is called the component of <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                        </math> orthogonal to <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
                        </math>.
				</para.body>
                     <index.symbol>
                        <symbol>
                           <math>
                              <latex>\pr_{\Vect{y}}(\Vect{x})</latex>
                           </math>
                        </symbol>
                        <info>
                           <para>
                              <para.body>
                                 <math>
                                    <latex>\pr_{\Vect{y}}(\Vect{x}) := \dfrac{ \Vect{x} \bullet \Vect{y} }{ \Vect{y} \bullet \Vect{y} } \cdot \Vect{y}</latex>
                                 </math> is the orthogonal projection of the vector <math>
                                    <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                                 </math> along the nonzero vector <math>
                                    <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
                                 </math>.</para.body>
                           </para>
                        </info>
                     </index.symbol>
                     <index.glossary>
                        <term>orthogonal</term>
                        <term>projection of a vector along another</term>
                        <info>
                           <para>
                              <para.body>The orthogonal projection of a vector <math>
                                    <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                                 </math> along <math>
                                    <latex>\Vect{y} \neq \Vect{0}</latex>
                                 </math> is the vector </para.body>
                           </para>
                           <math.display>
                              <latex>\pr_{\Vect{y}}(\Vect{x}) := \dfrac{\Vect{x} \bullet \Vect{y} }{\Vect{y} \bullet \Vect{y} \cdot \Vect{y}</latex>
                           </math.display>
                        </info>
                     </index.glossary>
                     <index.glossary>
                        <term>component</term>
                        <term>of a vector orthogonal to another</term>
                        <info>
                           <para>
                              <para.body>The component of a vector <math>
                                    <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                                 </math> orthogonal to another vector <math>
                                    <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
                                 </math> is</para.body>
                           </para>
                           <math.display>
                              <latex>\Vect{u} = \Vect{x} - \pr_{\Vect{y}}(\Vect{x})</latex>
                           </math.display>
                        </info>
                     </index.glossary>
                  </para>
               </def.body>
            </def>
         </block.body>
      </block>
